# Git workflow (single agent, trunk)

Assume **one agent session at a time** on this repo. No parallel agents or
long-lived topic branches unless the user explicitly asks for them.

## Trunk and linear history

- Work on the default branch (e.g. `main`). Do not create feature branches for
  routine handoff implementation.
- Before continuing after the remote may have moved, use `git pull --rebase`
  (not `git pull` merge) so history stays a straight line.
- Avoid merge commits for integrating your own work. Do not merge unrelated
  local branches into `main` without user direction.
- Do **not** `git push --force` to the shared default branch unless the user
  explicitly requests it.

## Commit cadence during handoffs

When implementing work described in `docs/handoffs/*.md`, or when the user
asks you to implement a multi-step change and keep the repo updated:

1. **Commit often** — after each coherent, working increment (one logical
   concern per commit), not only at the end of the session.
2. **Keep commits small** — prefer several focused commits over one large
   commit that mixes scaffolding, unrelated refactors, and behavior changes.
3. **Stage narrowly** — use explicit paths or `git add -p` so unrelated edits
   do not ride along. Do not commit generated noise (build artifacts, editor
   junk) unless the user asked to track them.
4. **Message format** — follow `.cursor/rules/commit-message.mdc`
   (Conventional Commits, subject/body line width). Optionally mention the
   handoff file name in the body for traceability.

If the user clearly says **not** to commit (e.g. exploration only), respect
that and only inspect with `git status` / `git diff`.

## Session hygiene

- End a work block with a **clean** working tree when possible: everything
  committed or explicitly left unstaged for a reason the user knows.
- If you must stop mid-change, prefer a **WIP commit** with a honest subject
  (e.g. `chore(gravnav): wip scaffold package layout`) over large uncommitted
  diffs, unless the user forbids WIP commits.
